  "text": "For the same networks, transfer entropy was computed as a function of the latency between the past of dynamics of one source and a future of the dynamics of another source (k = 1, 2,. . .,50), for all possible pairs of the sources (30 connections in total) and for all single trials. Following [CITATION_1] , the transfer entropy was averaged across the latency k with the idea to decrease the variability of estimated statistics and to increase Frontiers in Systems Neuroscience www.frontiersin.org the robustness of the results. Note that as the MEG epochs were relatively short, the transfer entropy was computed only at time scale θ = 1, which corresponds to the original time series. For each trial and pathway, the information transfer was estimated in both directions: I k (x → y) and I k (y → x), as described in Section 6. The net information transfer was computed as the difference between two amounts of transfer entropy, averaged across trials. Thus, for a network of six sources, each pathway between two sources was associated with a value of the net information transfer, reflecting the asymmetry in the predictive power between the source activity.",
